The '''AeroVironment Switchblade''' is a family of man-portable [[loitering munition]]s designed by [[AeroVironment]] and used by several branches of the [[United States Armed Forces|United States military]] and also exported to other countries. Small enough to fit in a backpack, the Switchblade launches from a tube, flies to the target area, and crashes into its target while detonating its explosive warhead. The name ''[[Switchblade]]'' comes from how the spring-loaded wings are folded inside a tube and flipped out once released.<ref name=avinc1/>

Introduced in 2011, the original Switchblade was rebranded the '''Switchblade{{nbsp}}300''' after the much larger and very different '''Switchblade{{nbsp}}600''' anti-armour variant was unveiled in 2020. The [[#Blackwing|Blackwing]], an unarmed variant of the Switchblade{{nbsp}}300, was released in 2015. More than 700 Switchblade 300 drones were sent to [[Armed Forces of Ukraine|Ukraine]] by the United States as part of an arms package after the [[2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine]].<ref>{{Cite web |title= Fact Sheet on U.S. Security Assistance for Ukraine |url= https://www.war.gov/News/Releases/Release/Article/3027295/fact-sheet-on-us-security-assistance-for-ukraine/ |access-date= 2022-05-12 |publisher= U.S. Department of Defense |language= en-US |archive-date= 2022-05-11 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20220511205349/https://www.defense.gov/News/Releases/Release/Article/3027295/fact-sheet-on-us-security-assistance-for-ukraine/ |url-status= live }}</ref>

==History==
Designed by the United States [[Air Force Special Operations Command]] (AFSOC) and developed by the [[United States Army]],<ref name="c4isr13aug15" /> the Switchblade was designed to assist US troops in responding to enemy ambushes in Afghanistan. Close air support takes time to arrive, is costly to operate, and risks collateral damage in urban areas. Troop-carried guided missiles, such as the [[FGM-148 Javelin]], are also significantly larger, heavier, and more expensive, and only a few, if any, are carried on a typical patrol. Human-portable [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]s (UAVs) like the [[AeroVironment RQ-11 Raven|Raven]] or [[AeroVironment RQ-20 Puma|Puma]] can spot threats but lack weapons. The backpackable, relatively inexpensive Switchblade has sensors to help spot enemy fighters and an explosive warhead to attack them from above, which is especially helpful in dug-in positions like rooftops or ridge lines.

On July 29, 2011, the U.S. Army awarded [[AeroVironment]] a $4.9 million contract for "rapid fielding" of an unspecified number of Switchblades to forces in [[Afghanistan]].<ref name="wired18oct11" /><ref name="wired12march13" /><ref>{{Cite web |last=Tarantola |first=Andrew |date=5 September 2013 |title=America's Kamikaze Drone Makes the Skies Way Less Friendly |url=https://gizmodo.com/americas-kamikaze-drone-makes-the-skies-way-less-frien-1227821895 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829193301/http://gizmodo.com/americas-kamikaze-drone-makes-the-skies-way-less-frien-1227821895 |archive-date=29 August 2017 |website=Gizmodo}}</ref> On March 20, 2012, the Army added $5.1 million, totaling $10 million.<ref>{{Cite web |date=23 May 2012 |title=U.S. Army Awards AeroVironment $5.1 Million Order for Switchblade Loitering Munition Systems and Services |url=https://www.avinc.com/resources/press-releases/view/u.s._army_awards_aerovironment_5.1_million_order_for_switchblade_loitering_ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240102235327/https://www.avinc.com/resources/press-releases/view/u.s._army_awards_aerovironment_5.1_million_order_for_switchblade_loitering_ |archive-date=2 January 2024 |website=AeroVironment}}</ref>

In May 2012, the [[United States Marine Corps]] began ordering Switchblades to allow troops to strike [[improvised explosive device]] (IED) emplacement teams and similar targets. Usually, when air support is called in, attackers slip away before a large UAV, attack helicopter, fighter bomber, or quick reaction force can arrive at the station. Marines sometimes couldn't get support due to other units getting mission priority. The Switchblade is small enough to fit in a Marine's [[ALICE pack|ALICE]] or [[MOLLE]] pack and locks onto and tracks a target once selected.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Sanborn |first=James K. |date=16 May 2012 |title=Marine Corps pursues 'kamikaze' drone |url=http://www.marinecorpstimes.com/article/20120516/NEWS/205160317/Marine-Corps-pursues-8216-kamikaze-drone |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140425025856/http://www.marinecorpstimes.com/article/20120516/NEWS/205160317/Marine-Corps-pursues-8216-kamikaze-drone |archive-date=25 April 2014 |website=Marine Corps Times}}</ref>

In late 2012, 75 Switchblades were supplied to U.S. soldiers in Afghanistan. Several successful employments had occurred by January 2013. Although the military would not confirm details about its deployment, effectiveness, distribution, or tactical employment, commanders reported that it was "very effective." Shortly after, the Army theatre commanders requested a joint urgent needs statement for more systems. The number requested was not specified but was "dramatically more" than the 75 systems initially supplied and exceeded budget limitations. The Switchblade gained notoriety among soldiers using it and insurgents targeted by it. The Army classifies it as a direct-fire munition rather than a drone.<ref name="wired12march13"/><ref>[https://archive.today/20140427195428/http://www.defensenews.com/article/20130212/DEFREG02/302120017/U-S-Army-Wants-More-Switchblades U.S. Army Wants More Switchblades] - Defensenews.com, 12 February 2013</ref>

Soldiers embraced it as a valuable tool, especially to reduce collateral damage. Unlike most other weapons, the Switchblade can wave off or abort a mission if the situation changes after launch, allowing it to engage a secondary target or destroy itself without inflicting casualties or property damage.<ref>[http://www.armytimes.com/article/20130814/NEWS04/308140013/Kamikaze-drones-Miniature-munitions-dismounted-troops Kamikaze drones: Miniature munitions for dismounted troops] - Armytimes.com, August 14, 2013,</ref> Wave off was used over a dozen times to prevent civilian casualties that could have been caused had a person not been in the decision loop.<ref name="c4isr13aug15"/>

On August 28, 2013, AeroVironment announced it had been awarded five contracts totaling $15.8 million to supply more Switchblade systems, ancillary equipment, and support to the Army.<ref>{{Cite web |date=28 August 2013 |title=AeroVironment wins US Army Switchblade award |url=https://www.shephardmedia.com/news/landwarfareintl/aerovironment-wins-us-army-switchblade-award/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131211155026/http://www.shephardmedia.com/news/landwarfareintl/aerovironment-wins-us-army-switchblade-award/ |archive-date=11 December 2013 |website=Shephard Media}}</ref> One week later, [[the Pentagon]] gave the company a follow-on contract worth $6.6 million. On September 5, 2013, AeroVironment was awarded a $29 million contract modification to supply Switchblade munitions systems and associated hardware and support services, totaling $51.4 million worth in contracts announced over nine days.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Smith |first=Rich |date=9 September 2013 |title=AeroVironment Reaps $51.4 Million in Switchblade UAV Contracts in 9 Days |url=http://www.suasnews.com/2013/09/24892/aerovironment-reaps-51-4-million-in-switchblade-uav-contracts-in-9-days/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131213120252/http://www.suasnews.com/2013/09/24892/aerovironment-reaps-51-4-million-in-switchblade-uav-contracts-in-9-days/ |archive-date=13 December 2013 |website=suasnews.com}}</ref>

In April 2015, the Marines test-fired a Switchblade from the back of an [[MV-22 Osprey]]. The drone was not equipped with a warhead but was successfully released and accurately steered toward a target. The test showed that the Switchblade could be air-launched from the aircraft and add a remotely controlled, weaponized surveillance tool to the Osprey.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bryant |first=Jordan |date=17 April 2015 |title=Marines Fire Switchblade Drone From Osprey in Test |url=http://defensetech.org/2015/04/17/marines-fire-switchblade-drone-from-osprey-in-test/ |url-status=usurped |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150419153932/http://defensetech.org/2015/04/17/marines-fire-switchblade-drone-from-osprey-in-test/ |archive-date=19 April 2015 |website=defensetech.org}}</ref> From its introduction to the end of [[Operation Enduring Freedom - Afghanistan|Operation Enduring Freedom]], over 4,000 switchblades were deployed in Afghanistan.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Hambling |first=David |date=15 January 2016 |title=Will 2016 be the Year of the Portable Lethal Drone? |url=http://defensetech.org/2016/01/15/will-2016-be-the-year-of-the-portable-lethal-drone/ |url-status=usurped |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160117033023/http://defensetech.org/2016/01/15/will-2016-be-the-year-of-the-portable-lethal-drone/ |archive-date=17 January 2016 |website=defensetech.org}}</ref> In mid-2017, 350 Switchblades were delivered to [[United States Special Operations Command|SOCOM]] for use against [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Tucker |first=Patrick |date=18 May 2017 |title=In Urgent Request, US Special Ops Adds 350 Kamikaze Drones to Fight ISIS |url=https://www.defenseone.com/technology/2017/05/Special-Ops-Gets-350-More-Kamikaze-Suicide-Drones-to-Fight-ISIS/137987/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170604082453/http://www.defenseone.com/technology/2017/05/Special-Ops-Gets-350-More-Kamikaze-Suicide-Drones-to-Fight-ISIS/137987/?oref=d-river |archive-date=4 June 2017 |access-date= |website=Defense One |language=en}}</ref>

On April 28, 2016, AeroVironment announced they had developed an upgrade for the Switchblade Tactical Missile System, designated Block 10C. In October 2016, AeroVironment announced the Multi-Pack Launcher (MPL), a system to carry and remotely launch several Switchblades.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |last=Magnuson |first=Stew |date=16 July 2019 |title=Multi-Pack Launcher Deployed for Switchblade |url=https://www.nationaldefensemagazine.org/articles/2019/7/16/multi-pack-launcher-deployed-for-switchblade |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721192103/https://www.nationaldefensemagazine.org/articles/2019/7/16/multi-pack-launcher-deployed-for-switchblade |archive-date=21 July 2019 |website=National Defense}}</ref>

In October 2020, AeroVironment announced a project with [[Kratos Defense & Security Solutions|Kratos Defence & Security Solutions]] to demonstrate a "high-speed, long-range unmanned combat air vehicle" that serves as a mothership to deliver Switchblade 300s in large numbers that cooperatively attacks and overwhelms enemy defences.<ref name="defensenews2oct20">{{Cite web |last=Judson |first=Jen |date=2 October 2020 |title=AeroVironment debuts bigger, anti-armor loitering missile |url=https://www.defensenews.com/land/2020/10/01/aerovironment-debuts-bigger-anti-armor-loitering-missile/ |access-date= |website=Defense News |language=en |archive-date=26 February 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240226103133/https://www.defensenews.com/land/2020/10/01/aerovironment-debuts-bigger-anti-armor-loitering-missile/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In late 2018, AeroVironment was working on the larger Switchblade 600.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Reim |first=Garrett |date=9 October 2018 |title=AeroVironment to integrate Switchblade and Shrike 2 onto armoured vehicles |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/civil-uavs/aerovironment-to-integrate-switchblade-and-shrike-2-onto-armoured-vehicles/129809.article |access-date= |website=Flight Global |language=en |archive-date=17 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220317042051/https://www.flightglobal.com/civil-uavs/aerovironment-to-integrate-switchblade-and-shrike-2-onto-armoured-vehicles/129809.article |url-status=live }}</ref> In March 2020, AeroVironment revealed it had flight tested the product the previous year. In October 2020, AeroVironment unveiled the larger unit. By the time of its unveiling, it had undergone 60 test flights from ground launches against fixed and moving targets.<ref name="defensenews2oct20" /><ref name="AviationWeekOct01">{{cite web |last1=Trimble |first1=Steve |title=AeroVironment Unveils Switchblade 600 Loitering Missile {{!}} Aviation Week Network |url=https://aviationweek.com/defense-space/missile-defense-weapons/aerovironment-unveils-switchblade-600-loitering-missile |website=aviationweek.com |date=1 October 2020 |access-date=3 October 2020 |archive-date=18 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220318224052/https://aviationweek.com/defense-space/missile-defense-weapons/aerovironment-unveils-switchblade-600-loitering-missile |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite web |last=Szondy |first=David |date=5 October 2020 |title=Switchblade 600 drone provides improved loitering missile capability |url=https://newatlas.com/military/switchblade-600-loitering-drone/ |website=New Atlas |access-date=22 October 2020 |archive-date=16 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220316020746/https://newatlas.com/military/switchblade-600-loitering-drone/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

On March 31, 2021, AeroVironment was awarded a US$26.1 million contract by SOCOM for the Switchblade 600. The system addresses the [[United States Naval Special Warfare Command]]'s Maritime Precision Engagement (MPE) requirement to engage asymmetric threats with Combatant Craft Medium (CCM) and Heavy (CCH) boats acting as host platforms.<ref>{{Cite web |last= |first= |date=28 April 2021 |title=Switchblade 600 loitering missile to equip US Naval Special Warfare craft |url=https://www.janes.com/defence-news/news-detail/switchblade-600-loitering-missile-to-equip-us-naval-special-warfare-craft |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210430110029/https://www.janes.com/defence-news/news-detail/switchblade-600-loitering-missile-to-equip-us-naval-special-warfare-craft |archive-date=30 April 2021 |access-date=2 May 2021 |website=[[Jane's Information Group]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=28 April 2021 |title=AeroVironment awarded $26 Million Switchblade 600 tactical missile systems contract by US Special Operation Command |url=https://www.airrecognition.com/index.php/news/defense-aviation-news/2021/april/7253-aerovironment-awarded-26-million-switchblade-600-tactical-missile-systems-contract-by-us-special-operation-command.html |access-date= |website=www.airrecognition.com |archive-date=16 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220316033251/https://www.airrecognition.com/index.php/news/defense-aviation-news/2021/april/7253-aerovironment-awarded-26-million-switchblade-600-tactical-missile-systems-contract-by-us-special-operation-command.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

In March 2022, it was reported that the US was considering providing Switchblade drones to the [[Ukrainian armed forces]] following the [[2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine|Russian invasion of Ukraine]].<ref name="NBC20220316">{{cite news |last1=Dilanian |first1=Ken |last2=Luce |first2=Dan De |last3=Kube |first3=Courtney |date=2022-03-16 |title=Biden admin weighs providing Ukraine with killer drones called Switchblades |publisher=NBC News |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/ukraine-asks-biden-admin-armed-drones-jamming-gear-surface-air-missile-rcna20197 |url-status=live |access-date=2022-03-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220316125927/https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/national-security/ukraine-asks-biden-admin-armed-drones-jamming-gear-surface-air-missile-rcna20197 |archive-date=2022-03-16}}</ref> On March 16, the White House announced that "100 Tactical Unmanned Aerial Systems" would be provided to Ukraine as part of an $800 million military aid package.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://bidenwhitehouse.archives.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2022/03/16/fact-sheet-on-u-s-security-assistance-for-ukraine/ |website=[[White House]] |title=Fact Sheet on U.S. Security Assistance for Ukraine |date=16 March 2022 |access-date=30 March 2022 |archive-date=24 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220324032158/https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/statements-releases/2022/03/16/fact-sheet-on-u-s-security-assistance-for-ukraine/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Another 600 systems were announced to be sent in April,<ref>{{Cite web |last=Shankland |first=Stephen |date=15 April 2022 |title=US Military Sends Another 600 Switchblade Drones to Ukraine |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/us-military-sends-another-600-switchblade-drones-to-ukraine/ |access-date= |website=CNET |language=en |archive-date=3 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221103220509/https://www.cnet.com/news/us-military-sends-another-600-switchblade-drones-to-ukraine/ |url-status=live }}</ref> bringing the total number of munitions sent to Ukraine to 700.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Hambling |first=David |date=8 June 2022 |title=Failure Or Savior? Busting Myths About Switchblade Loitering Munitions In Ukraine |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/davidhambling/2022/06/08/failure-or-savior-busting-myths-about-switchblade-loitering-munitions-in-ukraine/ |access-date=8 June 2022 |website=Forbes |language=en |archive-date=8 June 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220608112355/https://www.forbes.com/sites/davidhambling/2022/06/08/failure-or-savior-busting-myths-about-switchblade-loitering-munitions-in-ukraine/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Ukraine first reported using a Switchblade on a Russian target in Kharkiv Oblast in early May. A Switchblade 300 was used against a bunker; it is unclear if it was shot down or completed its task by exploding. Russian forces recovered the remains.<ref>{{cite web |last=Roblin |first=Sebastien |date=6 May 2022 |title=First Video Emerges Of Switchblade Drone Kamikazeing Into Russian Infantry In Ukraine |url=https://www.19fortyfive.com/2022/05/first-video-emerges-of-switchblade-drone-kamikazeing-into-russian-infantry-in-ukraine/ |access-date=7 May 2022 |publisher=19fortyfive.com |archive-date=7 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220507010659/https://www.19fortyfive.com/2022/05/first-video-emerges-of-switchblade-drone-kamikazeing-into-russian-infantry-in-ukraine/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Nikolov |first=Boyko |date=6 May 2022 |title=First recorded use of US-made Switchblade 300 kamikaze in Ukraine |url=https://bulgarianmilitary.com/amp/2022/05/06/first-recorded-use-of-us-made-switchblade-300-kamikaze-in-ukraine/ |access-date=7 May 2022 |publisher=Bulgarian Military |archive-date=7 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220507093754/https://bulgarianmilitary.com/amp/2022/05/06/first-recorded-use-of-us-made-switchblade-300-kamikaze-in-ukraine/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=6 May 2022 |title=Switchblade 300: the Ukrainian Armed Forces have probably used the American kamikaze drone for the first time |url=https://mil.in.ua/en/news/switchblade-300-the-ukrainian-armed-forces-have-probably-used-the-american-kamikaze-drone-for-the-first-time/ |website=Militarnyi |access-date=7 May 2022 |archive-date=7 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220507120336/https://mil.in.ua/en/news/switchblade-300-the-ukrainian-armed-forces-have-probably-used-the-american-kamikaze-drone-for-the-first-time/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Despite receiving hundreds of Switchblade drones, some Ukrainian units prefer to use commercial drones equipped with explosives that are easier to use.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lillis |first1=Katie Bo |last2=Starr |first2=Barbara |last3=Bertrand |first3=Natasha |last4=Liebermann |first4=Oren |date=14 June 2022 |title=War in Ukraine reaches pivotal moment that could determine long-term outcome, intelligence officials say |newspaper=CNN |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2022/06/14/politics/ukraine-war-pivotal-moment-intelligence-officials-loses-in-the-east-russia/index.html |access-date=7 July 2022 |archive-date=7 July 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220707034717/https://edition.cnn.com/2022/06/14/politics/ukraine-war-pivotal-moment-intelligence-officials-loses-in-the-east-russia/index.html |url-status=live }}</ref> The U.S. planned to also send the anti-armour Switchblade 600,<ref>{{Cite web |date=5 April 2022 |title=US Switchblade Drones for Ukraine Will Include Tank Killers |url=https://www.military.com/daily-news |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220405173109/https://www.military.com/daily-news/2022/04/05/us-switchblade-drones-ukraine-will-include-tank-killers.html |archive-date=5 April 2022 |access-date= |website=Military.com |language=en}}</ref> but although the Switchblade 300 was delivered soon after being pledged to Ukraine, the larger Switchblade 600 was not because it was still a prototype and not considered a fielded capability, so it had to complete testing and evaluation.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Gould |first=Joe |date=22 August 2022 |title=Delayed kamikaze drone for Ukraine on track for next month: Pentagon |url=https://www.defensenews.com/pentagon/2022/08/22/delayed-kamikaze-drone-for-ukraine-on-track-for-next-month-pentagon/ |access-date= |website=Defense News |language=en |archive-date=26 February 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240226103143/https://www.defensenews.com/pentagon/2022/08/22/delayed-kamikaze-drone-for-ukraine-on-track-for-next-month-pentagon/ |url-status=live }}</ref> While the Switchblade 300 has been used against soft Russian targets like fuel trucks, personnel carriers, machine gun nests, trench positions, and dismounted infantry, the Switchblade 600 can be used against heavy armour, including tanks. In October 2022, AeroVironment said the first batch of 10 Switchblade 600s would likely be in Ukraine "in the next few weeks."<ref name="defensenews11oct22">{{Cite web |last=Losey |first=Stephen |date=2022-10-11 |title=Switchblade kamikaze drone production to ramp up following Ukraine use |url=https://www.defensenews.com/digital-show-dailies/ausa/2022/10/11/switchblade-kamikaze-drone-production-to-ramp-up-following-ukraine-use/ |access-date=2023-08-31 |website=Defense News |language=en |archive-date=2024-02-26 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240226103149/https://www.defensenews.com/digital-show-dailies/ausa/2022/10/11/switchblade-kamikaze-drone-production-to-ramp-up-following-ukraine-use/ |url-status=live }}</ref> They were reportedly delivered by the end of the year, and were first used in combat in spring 2023.<ref name="popularmechanics21april23">{{cite web |last=Roblin |first=Sébastien |date=21 April 2023 |title=Watch the First Confirmed Use of a Tank-Busting Switchblade-600 Drone in Ukraine |url=https://www.popularmechanics.com/military/weapons/a43660797/first-confirmed-use-tank-busting-switchblade-600-drone-in-ukraine-video/ |website=[[Popular Mechanics]] |access-date=5 June 2023 |archive-date=5 June 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230605020254/https://www.popularmechanics.com/military/weapons/a43660797/first-confirmed-use-tank-busting-switchblade-600-drone-in-ukraine-video/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

Ukraine initially used the Switchblade-300, but the system's use gradually declined because Russia improved its air defense and electronic warfare systems.<ref name="auto">{{Cite web |last=Satam |first=Parth |date=25 July 2023 |title=US' 'Cutting-Edge' Switchblade-600 Drone "Downed" By Russian Electronic Warfare; Viral Videos Show Near-Intact Munition |url=https://www.eurasiantimes.com/us-most-advanced-switchblade-600-drone-downed-by/ |access-date=26 July 2023 |archive-date=26 July 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230726153812/https://www.eurasiantimes.com/us-most-advanced-switchblade-600-drone-downed-by/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Jamming is likely responsible for the majority of drone losses in the conflict, and according to three unnamed Ukrainian officers in April and May 2023, Ukraine was losing 10,000 drones a month to Russian electronic-warfare systems that spoofed signals and interfered with their navigation.<ref name="popularmechanics21april23"/><ref>{{cite web |last=Jankowicz |first=Mia |date=22 May 2023 |title=Ukraine is losing 10,000 drones a month to Russian electronic-warfare systems that send fake signals and screw with their navigation, researchers say |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/ukraine-losing-10000-drones-month-russia-electronic-warfare-rusi-report-2023-5 |website=[[Business Insider]] |access-date=5 June 2023 |archive-date=31 May 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230531204031/https://www.businessinsider.com/ukraine-losing-10000-drones-month-russia-electronic-warfare-rusi-report-2023-5 |url-status=live }}</ref> AeroVironment later improved the Switchblade 600's resistance to jamming through software updates and better operator training.<ref>[https://www.defenseone.com/technology/2024/05/new-details-give-replicator-distinct-ukrainian-flavor/396344/ New details give Replicator a distinct Ukrainian flavor]. ''Defense One''. 6 May 2024.</ref>

[[File:Low Altitude Stalking and Strike Ordnance (LASSO) (Switchblade 600).jpg|thumb|Low Altitude Stalking and Strike Ordnance (LASSO)]]
The U.S. Army ordered more than 100 Switchblade 600s in October 2023 as part of the first increment of the Low Altitude Stalking and Strike Ordnance (LASSO) program; they will be operated at [[company (military unit)|company]]-level.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Roque |first=Ashley |date=13 October 2023 |title=Army awaiting 100-plus Switchblade 600 attack drones |url=https://breakingdefense.sites.breakingmedia.com/2023/10/army-awaiting-100-plus-switchblade-600-attack-drones/ |access-date= |website=Breaking Defense |language=en-US |archive-date=26 February 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240226103152/https://breakingdefense.com/2023/10/army-awaiting-100-plus-switchblade-600-attack-drones/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

On June 11, 2024, a Switchblade, believed to be a 600 or improved model, struck a Russian [[Buk missile system|Buk]] missile launcher in Sarabash (formerly Komunarivka), Donetsk. The drone had to "travel more than 30 kilometers".<ref>{{cite web |last=Hambling |first=David |date=11 June 2024 |title=Switchblade Long-Range Loitering Munition Destroys Russian Buk SAM|url=https://mil.in.ua/en/news/switchblade-long-range-loitering-munition-destroys-russian-buk-sam/ |website=mil.in.ua |access-date=12 June 2024}}</ref>

In August 2024, the U.S. Army awarded AeroVironment a contract worth nearly $1 billion to deliver Switchblade 300 and 600 drones over the next five years.<ref>[https://www.twz.com/air/army-just-signed-1b-deal-for-massive-order-of-switchblade-kamikaze-drones Army Just Signed $1B Deal For Massive Order Of Switchblade Kamikaze Drones]. ''The War Zone''. 28 August 2024.</ref><ref>[https://www.defensenews.com/land/2024/08/28/aerovironment-wins-nearly-1b-to-supply-switchblade-munitions-to-army/ Aerovironment wins nearly $1B to supply Switchblade munitions to Army]. ''[[Defense News]]''. 28 August 2024.</ref>

On February 26, 2026, AeroVironment announced receipt of a $186 million delivery order from the U.S. Army for Switchblade 600 Block 2 and Switchblade 300 Block 20 - as part of the aforementioned $990 million "Indefinite Delivery, Indefinite Quantity" (IDIQ) contract.<ref>{{Cite web |title=AV Receives $186 Million U.S. Army Delivery Order for Next-Generation Switchblade Systems |url=https://investor.avinc.com/news-releases/news-release-details/av-receives-186-million-us-army-delivery-order-next-generation}}</ref>

==Design==
===Switchblade 300===
[[File:Switchblade 300 in flight (200902-M-EU630-1102) (cropped).jpg|thumb|alt=Switchblade 300 in flight|Switchblade 300 in flight]]
The Switchblade 300 is designed as an expendable UAV to offer precision firepower for [[platoon]]-sized infantry units.

It helps engage long-range targets and assists in relieving units pinned down by enemy fire. It can identify, track, and engage targets and follow a pre-programmed course.

It has been used to destroy light armoured vehicles and personnel. The operator can call to re-target a unit en route.<ref name="wired18oct11" /><ref name="wired12march13" /><ref name="gizmodo5sept13" /> Its small size and silent flight make it extremely difficult to detect or intercept.

[[File:Switchblade 300 unit.jpg|thumb|Launch unit for the Switchblade 300. Compressed air is used to expel the drone from the tube.]]
The Switchblade uses the same Ground Control Station (GCS) as other AeroVironment UAVs, including the [[AeroVironment Wasp III|Wasp]], [[RQ-11 Raven]], and [[AeroVironment RQ-20 Puma|RQ-20 Puma]]. This creates a commonality and the potential for teaming of longer-endurance small UAVs to recon for targets, then having the Switchblade attack once they are identified with the same controller.<ref name="wired18oct11">{{Cite web |last=Ackerman |first=Spencer |date=10 October 2011 |title=U.S. Troops Will Soon Get Tiny Kamikaze Drone |url=https://www.wired.com/2011/10/tiny-kamikaze-drone/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170302180326/https://www.wired.com/2011/10/tiny-kamikaze-drone/ |archive-date=2 March 2017 |website=Wired.com}}</ref><ref name="wired12march13">{{Cite web |last=Ackerman |first=Spencer |date=12 March 2013 |title=Tiny, Suicidal Drone/Missile Mashup Is Part of U.S.' Afghanistan Arsenal |url=https://www.wired.com/2013/03/switchblade-afghanistan/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161223062807/https://www.wired.com/2013/03/switchblade-afghanistan/ |archive-date=23 December 2016 |website=Wired.com}}</ref><ref name="gizmodo5sept13">[https://gizmodo.com/americas-kamikaze-drone-makes-the-skies-way-less-frien-1227821895 America's Kamikaze Drone Makes the Skies Way Less Friendly] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170829193301/http://gizmodo.com/americas-kamikaze-drone-makes-the-skies-way-less-frien-1227821895 |date=2017-08-29 }} - Gizmodo.com, 5 September 2013</ref><ref>[http://www.army-technology.com/features/featurekamikaze-drones-military-robots-self-destruct/ Kamikaze drones - the military robots set to self-destruct] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151003020402/http://www.army-technology.com/features/featurekamikaze-drones-military-robots-self-destruct/ |date=2015-10-03 }} - Army-Technology.com, 6 August 2012</ref>{{Unreliable source?|reason=domain on WP:BLACKLIST|date=June 2016}}

The warhead is designed for controlled firepower to reduce collateral damage through a focused blast. It has a forward-firing [[shotgun]]-blast effect rather than a 360-degree blast, expelling pellets in the direction that the missile is traveling. It can be fused to detonate at a predetermined height, which can be adjusted mid-flight. When diving, the operator can cancel the attack until four seconds from impact. The warhead can be detonated mid-flight to destroy it.<ref name="c4isr13aug15" />

The U.S. Army categorizes the Switchblade as a [[missile]] rather than a drone. The term "[[loitering munition]]" is preferred. Unlike UAVs, it is not recoverable once launched. Its operation is similar to the wireless [[TOW missile]] through a fly-by-radio frequency signal. The TOW doesn't loiter, but both have the same operator-in-the-loop characteristics.<ref name="c4isr13aug15" />

The Switchblade does not fit into established doctrines since it is not an armed reconnaissance vehicle dispatched by a platoon commander to scout over an area and destroy enemies, or an [[intelligence, surveillance, and reconnaissance]] (ISR) platform, as its cameras are for viewing targets instead of recon. It meets the need for squads and platoons that lack high-level intelligence and communications to fire missiles beyond the ranges they are trying to influence.<ref name="c4isr13aug15">{{Cite web |last=Peck |first=Michael |date=13 August 2015 |title='Kamikaze drones' add a new layer of lethality to remote forces |url=http://www.c4isrnet.com/story/military-tech/omr/missile-defense/2015/08/13/kamikaze-drones-add-new-layer-lethality-remote-forces/31405521/ |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150919193839/http://www.c4isrnet.com/story/military-tech/omr/missile-defense/2015/08/13/kamikaze-drones-add-new-layer-lethality-remote-forces/31405521/ |archive-date=19 September 2015 |website=c4isrnet.com}}</ref>

[[SRC Inc.]] developed software to combine the Switchblade with sensors to intercept hostile UAVs. The Switchblade is used alongside an existing [[Counter-battery radar|counter-artillery radar]] and [[Improvised explosive device|IED]] jamming system, all of which can be towed by [[Humvee]]s. Interception of an enemy drone occurs in layers: if a drone gets through covering fighters or is too small to be targeted by them, it is picked up by the fire-finding radar. Once detected, the jammer performs [[electronic warfare]] to break its [[data link]]. If the drone resists EW, a Switchblade is launched to impact and destroy it physically.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Clark |first=Colin |date=2014-10-13 |title=New Weapons Spell Death For Drones; The Countermeasure Dance |url=https://breakingdefense.com/2014/10/new-weapons-spell-death-for-drones-the-countermeasure-dance/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017041946/http://breakingdefense.com/2014/10/new-weapons-spell-death-for-drones-the-countermeasure-dance/ |archive-date=2014-10-17 |access-date=2024-01-02 |website=Breaking Defense |language=en-US}}</ref>

==== Block 10C ====
Each Block 10C unit is {{convert |2|ft|mm|abbr= on}} long and weighs {{convert |6|lb|kg|abbr=on}} including the carrying case and launcher, making it small and light enough for one soldier to carry. It can be controlled at distances of up to {{convert |10|km|mi|abbr=on}}. Flight time is 10 minutes. It is equipped with (daytime) color and [[infrared camera]]s and a [[GPS]] locator. Its warhead is equivalent to a [[40 mm grenade]]. An electric motor propels the aircraft and can reach speeds of {{convert|85|knot|mph km/h}}.

The Switchblade uses daytime, as well as an "aided target tracker" to lock on to stationary and moving targets.<ref name="c4isr13aug15" />

Block 10C incorporates a Digital Data Link (DDL) to provide a stable and secure encrypted communication link through more efficient use of existing frequency bands and significantly reduced likelihood of signal interception{{Citation needed|date=October 2025}}, as well as concurrent operation of multiple Switchblade systems in the same vicinity without signal conflict, gives opportunity to extend operational ranges using another DDL arbiter such as a different AeroVironment UAV, and facilitates sensor to shooter operations through automatic communication of mission plans from one AeroVironment UAS to a Switchblade.<ref>{{Cite web |date=29 April 2016 |title=AeroVironment begins production of Switchblade Tactical Missile System upgrade |url=https://armyrecognition.com/april_2016_global_defense_security_news_industry/aerovironment_begins_production_of_switchblade_tactical_missile_system_upgrade_52904163.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701034013/http://armyrecognition.com/april_2016_global_defense_security_news_industry/aerovironment_begins_production_of_switchblade_tactical_missile_system_upgrade_52904163.html |archive-date=1 July 2017 |website=Army Recognition}}</ref>

The Multi-Pack Launcher (MPL) remotely launches multiple Switchblades. The MPL is fully loaded in a standard 6-pack configuration weighing {{convert|160|lb|kg|abbr=on}}. The design is scalable from 2 to 20 rounds and enables rapid reloading of less than 30 seconds per round. The U.S. Army began deploying the MPL in early 2019 for base defense.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite web |date=2016-10-04 |title=AeroVironment Introduces New Remote-Controlled Multi-Pack Launcher for its Switchblade and Blackwing Tactical Missile Systems |url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20161004005621/en/AeroVironment-Introduces-New-Remote-Controlled-Multi-Pack-Launcher-for-its-Switchblade-and-Blackwing-Tactical-Missile-Systems |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024023931/http://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20161004005621/en/ |archive-date=2016-10-24 |access-date=2024-01-02 |website=www.businesswire.com |language=en}}</ref>

==== Block 20 ====
Block 20 increases flight time to 20 minutes. It features an improved DDL range. It has an EO/IR panning camera suite to provide real-time video and left-hand commit with continuous identification (PID).<ref>{{Cite web |last=Mehta |first=Aaron |date=29 March 2023 |title=AeroVironment upgrades Switchblade 300 with extended endurance |url=https://breakingdefense.com/2023/03/aerovironment-upgrades-switchblade-300-with-extended-endurance/ |website=Breaking Defense |access-date=2 April 2023 |archive-date=2 April 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230402182630/https://breakingdefense.com/2023/03/aerovironment-upgrades-switchblade-300-with-extended-endurance/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

It has a gross weight of about {{Convert|8|lb|abbr=on}}. The 4-lb (2-kg) unit can be launched in less than two minutes. The launch tube includes an integrated control and can support land, sea, and mobile platforms.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web |last=Szondy |first=David |date=2023-04-04 |title=AeroVironment introduces latest Switchblade 300 suicide drone |url=https://newatlas.com/military/aerovironment-introduces-latest-switchblade-300-suicide-drone/ |access-date=2023-04-04 |website=New Atlas |language=en-US |archive-date=2023-04-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230404021142/https://newatlas.com/military/aerovironment-introduces-latest-switchblade-300-suicide-drone/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

It can send back intelligence, such as GPS coordinates of targets.<ref name=":1" />

===Switchblade 600===
{{external media
| float  =right
| title  =External images
| image1 =[https://freeimage.host/a/switchblade-600-circuits.enqVS Photos of internal curcuits of the Switchblade 600]
}}
The larger Switchblade 600 loitering munition weighs {{cvt|54.5|kg|abbr=on}} including the all-up round in the tube and FCS;<ref>{{Cite web |last=Hughes |first=Robin |date=6 October 2020 |title=AeroVironment unveils Switchblade 600 loitering missile system |url=https://www.janes.com/defence-news/news-detail/aerovironment-unveils-switchblade-600-loitering-missile-system |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201008152748/https://www.janes.com/defence-news/news-detail/aerovironment-unveils-switchblade-600-loitering-missile-system |archive-date=8 October 2020 |access-date= |website=[[Janes Information Services]]}}</ref> the airframe weighs {{cvt|22.7|kg|abbr=on}}, with the fire control system consisting of a [[tablet computer|tablet]] and long-range antenna.<ref name=":3">{{Cite web |last=Valpolini |first=Paolo |date=2 October 2020 |title=Switchblade 600, the new Medium Range Loitering Munition |url=https://www.edrmagazine.eu/switchblade-600-the-new-medium-range-loitering-munition |website=European Defence Review |access-date=3 November 2022 |archive-date=3 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221103234413/https://www.edrmagazine.eu/switchblade-600-the-new-medium-range-loitering-munition |url-status=live }}</ref> The system is man-portable and can be set up in 10 minutes. It is designed to fly out to {{cvt|40|km|abbr=on}} in 20 minutes, then loiter for another 20 minutes (giving it an {{cvt|80|km|abbr=on}} total range), however, reaching its maximum capable range requires using two long-range antennas deployed on the field to relay command from one operator to another through the handoff capability of the data link. It attacks at a {{cvt|115|mph|abbr=on}} dash speed, carrying a warhead based on the one used on the Javelin ATGM, designed to neutralize armoured vehicles.<ref name=":3" /><ref>{{Cite web |title=Small skirmishes pose perfect opportunity for Switchblade success in Ukraine |last=Martin |first=Tim |website=Shephard |date=8 April 2022 |url=https://www.shephardmedia.com/news/defence-notes/small-skirmishes-pose-opportunity-for-switchblade-/ |access-date=13 April 2022 |archive-date=8 April 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220408120235/https://www.shephardmedia.com/news/defence-notes/small-skirmishes-pose-opportunity-for-switchblade-/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite AV media |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9W-zWi4w2oM&t=892s |title=AeroVironment Family of Loitering Missile Systems – Virtual Press Briefing |date=2020-10-14 |type=video |publisher=[[AeroVironment Inc.]] |time=14:52 |access-date=2022-03-18 |archive-date=2022-03-17 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220317204004/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9W-zWi4w2oM&t=892s |url-status=live }}</ref>

A touchscreen tablet-based fire control system can manually or autonomously control the munition. It is secured through onboard encrypted data links and Selective Availability Anti-Spoofing Module GPS with a patented wave-off capability. An optional pocket digital data link (DDL) module allows engagements beyond {{cvt|90|km|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{Cite AV media|last=Hanning|first=Todd|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9W-zWi4w2oM&t=794s|title=AeroVironment Family of Loitering Missile Systems – Virtual Press Briefing|date=2020-10-14|type=video|publisher=[[AeroVironment Inc.]]|time=13:14|access-date=2022-03-18|archive-date=2022-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220317225006/https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9W-zWi4w2oM&t=794s|url-status=live}}</ref> The larger Switchblade could be fitted with an anti-tank warhead while having a longer range and costing less than anti-tank missiles like the [[FGM-148 Javelin]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Reim |first=Garrett |date=5 March 2020 |title=AeroVironment starts flight testing larger Switchblade with greater range |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/military-uavs/aerovironment-starts-flight-testing-larger-switchblade-with-greater-range/137113.article |website=Flight Global |access-date=16 May 2020 |archive-date=16 June 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210616181106/https://www.flightglobal.com/military-uavs/aerovironment-starts-flight-testing-larger-switchblade-with-greater-range/137113.article |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Eastwood |first=Brent M. |date=16 March 2022 |title=Switchblade Kamikaze Drones: Russia's Worst Nightmare? |url=https://www.19fortyfive.com/2022/03/switchblade-kamikaze-drones-russias-worst-nightmare/ |access-date=17 March 2022 |website=19fortyfive.com |archive-date=17 March 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220317090417/https://www.19fortyfive.com/2022/03/switchblade-kamikaze-drones-russias-worst-nightmare/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

The Switchblade 600 was developed for the Army Single Multi-Mission Attack Missile development program. Other methods could include a six-pack vehicle-mounted version and by air-launch.<ref name="defensenews2oct20" /><ref name="AviationWeekOct01" /><ref name=":2"/>

In October 2022, AeroVironment said it was capable of producing more than 2,000 Switchblade 600 systems annually, and that it planned within a few months to increase production capacity to 6,000 per year.<ref name="defensenews11oct22"/>

===Blackwing===
First demonstrated in 2015, the AeroVironment Blackwing is an unarmed variant of the Switchblade{{nbsp}}300 with similar weight and dimensions. It was developed for the United States Navy to provide rapid [[Intelligence, surveillance, target acquisition, and reconnaissance#ISR|ISR (Intelligence, surveillance, and reconnaissance)]] as well as command and control relay operations among surface and undersea manned and unmanned vessels. The Blackwing can be deployed from a submerged submarine, surface ship, or mobile ground launcher.<ref name= avinc1 /><ref>{{cite web|access-date= 2022-03-16|title= Blackwing: Loitering Reconnaissance System|url= https://www.avinc.com/tms/blackwing|publisher= AeroVironment|archive-date= 2022-01-04|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20220104012921/https://www.avinc.com/tms/blackwing|url-status= live}}</ref>

